 Ship notes=
USS Indiana Battleship No. 1 was the lead ship of her Indiana class battleship class and the first United States Navy battleship equivalent to European designs of the time. Authorized in 1890 and commissioned five years later, she was a relatively small battleship with heavy armor and ordnance that pioneered the use of an Pre-dreadnought battleship#Armament intermediate battery. Specifically intended for Coastal defence and fortification coastal defense, her freeboard nautical freeboard was too low in the water to deal well with the waves of the open ocean and she also suffered from several design flaws.
Indiana served in the SpanishAmerican War as part of the North Atlantic Squadron, taking part in the blockade related to the Battle of Santiago de Cuba. Although unable to join the chase of the Spanish cruisers, she was partly responsible for the destruction of the Spanish destroyers Spanish destroyer Pluton Pluton and Spanish destroyer Furor Furor. After the war she became quickly obsoletedespite several modernizationsand spent most of her time in commission as a training ship or in the reserve fleet, with her last commission  during World War I as training ship for gun crews. She decommissioned for the third and final time in January 1919 and was shortly after reclassified Coast Battleship Number 1 so that the name Indiana could be reused. She was sunk as a target in underwater explosion and aerial bombing tests in 1920 and her hulk was sold for scrap.
Design and construction
Main Indiana class battleship
Indiana and her sister ships USS Massachusetts BB-2 Massachusetts and USS Oregon BB-3 Oregon were based on a modified version of a design for a short range battleship drawn up by a policy board in 1889. At the time United States Congress held the view that battleships should be coastline defenders rather than oceangoing long range battleships, because the latter were associated with Imperialism.Friedman, U.S. Battleships, p. 2425. This design view was reflected in their moderate endurance, relatively small Displacement ship displacement and low freeboard, which limited sea going capability.Gardiner, Steam, Steel & Shellfire: The Steam Warship 18151905, p. 121. They were however heavily armed and armored, so much in fact that Conway's All The Worlds Fighting Ships describes them as attempting too much on a very limited displacement.
cite book
   title = Conway's All the World's Fighting Ships, 1860-1905
   last1 = Chesneau  first1=Roger
   last2 = Kolenik  first2=Eugne M.
   last3 = Campbell first3=N.J.M.
   publisher = Conway Maritime Press
   date = 1979
   location = London
   isbn = 0851771335
  page = 140
The ships had a main battery of four 13-inch 330&nbsp;mm guns, an intermediate battery of eight 8-inch 200&nbsp;mm guns and a secondary battery of four 6-inch 150&nbsp;mm guns, twenty QF 6 pounder Hotchkiss Hotchkiss 6-pounders, and six QF 1 pounder pom-pom Maxim-Nordenfelt 1-pounders, as well as four 18-inch 460&nbsp;mm British 18 inch torpedo Whitehead torpedo tubes.Reilly & Scheina, American Battleships 18861923, p. 54-55. The main battery was placed in two centerline turrets fore and aft, while the intermediate battery was placed on four wing turrets on the superstructure. Because the turrets were not centrally balanced, they caused the ship to list when aimed broadside. During later modernizations counterweights and several other improvements were added,Reilly & Scheina, American Battleships 18861923, p. 62. but the gun mountings never performed in an entirely satisfactory manner.
Indianas armor consisted mostly of&mdash;what was at the time&mdash;modern Harvey armor. Its main protection was a 18-inch 460&nbsp;mm armor belt protecting the waterline of the central citadel. The hull above this belt and deck had a few inches of armor and below the belt the ship had a double bottom. On the ends the belt connected via armored bulkheads to the main barbettes, which were 17&nbsp;inches 430&nbsp;mm thick and the main turrets above them had 15&nbsp;inches 380&nbsp;mm of vertical plating. Armor for the 8-inch turrets and barbettes was less than half as thick and the hollow conning tower was 10&nbsp;inches 250&nbsp;mm of nickel steel.Reilly & Scheina, American Battleships 18861923, pp. 56, 58 & 68. The main armor belt was placed relatively low, causing it to be completely submerged when the ship was loaded with the maximum amount of coal and supplies and making it effectively useless.Friedman, U.S. Battleships, p. 29.
Two vertical inverted triple expansion reciprocating steam engines, powered by four Scotch marine boiler#Double-ended double ended Scotch boilers, produced convert 9700 ihp kW abbr=on lk=on. Indianas maximum speed was convert 15.5 knots km/h mph, slightly above her design speed of convert 15 knots km/h mph.Reilly & Scheina, American Battleships 18861923, pp. 58 & 68. The boilers were later replaced by eight Babcock & Wilcox boilers.
Service History
Early career
Indiana was commissioned on 20 November 1895 under the command of Captain nautical Captain Robley D. Evans, nicknamed Fighting Bob Evans.
